00:00:01.481 --> 00:00:02.980
LOGAN URY: Thank
you all for coming.

00:00:02.980 --> 00:00:06.010
This is the first in our series
about modern relationships,

00:00:06.010 --> 00:00:07.600
and it's great to
have you all here.

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:08.860
My name is Logan Ury.

00:00:08.860 --> 00:00:12.120
I help lead a team at Google
called the Irrational Lab.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:14.360
We're a behavioral
economics team.

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:16.610
And we're very lucky to
have Sherry Turkle here

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:20.400
today in a conversation
about conversations.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:24.010
Sherry is a MIT professor
who has spent the last 30

00:00:24.010 --> 00:00:26.600
years studying the psychology
of people's relationships

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:28.000
with technology.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.040
She's also the founder and
director of the MIT Initiative

00:00:31.040 --> 00:00:32.920
on Technology and Self.

00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:34.970
She's a licensed
psychologist and has

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:36.980
written four books
on our relationship

00:00:36.980 --> 00:00:38.550
with digital culture.

00:00:38.550 --> 00:00:42.370
These include "The Second
Self," "Life on the Screen,"

00:00:42.370 --> 00:00:45.999
"Alone Together," and now
"Reclaiming Conversation."

00:00:45.999 --> 00:00:47.040
Thank you for joining us.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:49.600
SHERRY TURKLE: I'm delighted
to be here-- really delighted

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:51.766
LOGAN URY: So today we'll
be covering your new book,

00:00:51.766 --> 00:00:53.930
"Reclaiming Conversation,"
how we can improve

00:00:53.930 --> 00:00:56.966
romantic relationships,
how this relates to Google,

00:00:56.966 --> 00:00:58.590
and then we'll open
it up to questions.

00:00:58.590 --> 00:00:59.370
SHERRY TURKLE: Wait a minute.

00:00:59.370 --> 00:00:59.650
Wait.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:00.170
LOGAN URY: Yeah?

00:01:00.170 --> 00:01:02.503
SHERRY TURKLE: How we can
improve romantic relationships

00:01:02.503 --> 00:01:04.099
and how that relates to Google?

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:05.129
LOGAN URY: There's
a comma in between.

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:05.572
SHERRY TURKLE: There's a comma.

00:01:05.572 --> 00:01:07.344
LOGAN URY: But it could
also be connected.

00:01:07.344 --> 00:01:09.610
SHERRY TURKLE: I feel like
I really prepared for this,

00:01:09.610 --> 00:01:12.410
and then all of a sudden
I felt unprepared.

00:01:12.410 --> 00:01:14.670
I'd really gotten
myself together,

00:01:14.670 --> 00:01:16.462
and then all of a sudden
I felt unprepared.

00:01:16.462 --> 00:01:17.920
LOGAN URY: And for
those of you who

00:01:17.920 --> 00:01:19.489
want to take out
that comma, we're

00:01:19.489 --> 00:01:21.530
going to open it up for
the questions at the end.

00:01:21.530 --> 00:01:23.640
SHERRY TURKLE: You have some
expertise I don't have, right.

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:24.590
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:01:24.590 --> 00:01:26.520
So just to start
off with the book,

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:29.250
you talk about how
reclaiming conversation

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:31.699
begins with reclaiming
our capacity for solitude.

00:01:31.699 --> 00:01:32.490
SHERRY TURKLE: Yes.

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:33.906
LOGAN URY: Can you
talk about what

00:01:33.906 --> 00:01:36.450
we lose when we're alone
because of our devices,

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:38.710
and what the value
of solitude is,

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:40.520
and how it's different
from loneliness?

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:41.394
SHERRY TURKLE: Right.

00:01:41.394 --> 00:01:44.210
Well, I think that this
probably-- the professor in me

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:46.500
wants to say that this
probably is the most

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:50.900
important piece of my argument.

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:53.720
And here's why.

00:01:53.720 --> 00:01:57.200
Criticisms of my work, even as
recently as a Pew study that

00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:02.166
came out just a few months
ago, people say things like,

00:02:02.166 --> 00:02:02.790
OK, well, look.

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:04.897
Let's give Sherry Turkle this.

00:02:04.897 --> 00:02:06.730
If you're together with
your friends and you

00:02:06.730 --> 00:02:10.500
take out a phone, not good.

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:12.620
Let's give her that, that
that kind of interrupts

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:15.340
the conversation and cuts
certain kinds of conversations

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:16.680
short.

00:02:16.680 --> 00:02:21.440
But if you're alone and
you take out your phone,

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:23.840
why does that bother her?

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:26.860
What's it to her if,
when you're alone,

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:32.440
you're on the constant feed
and you can't-- what is she,

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:34.080
the Darth Vader of the internet?

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:36.700
I mean, what's with that?

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.690
And actually I do
make the argument

00:02:40.690 --> 00:02:44.655
that solitude and the
capacity for conversation

00:02:44.655 --> 00:02:49.860
and relationship go together,
and they go together like this.

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:52.700
Solitude is the capacity
to be alone with yourself,

00:02:52.700 --> 00:02:58.520
to know who you are so that
when you come to another person,

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:02.550
you can hear what
they have to say

00:03:02.550 --> 00:03:06.040
and not-- you can listen to them
and hear what they have to say

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:09.610
and who they are, and
not need to project who

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:14.270
you need them to be on to them.

00:03:14.270 --> 00:03:17.300
And we all know that
when we meet somebody

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:21.060
who doesn't know who they
are, and who can't stand

00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:24.920
to be alone, and comes
to us for, quote,

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:28.210
"conversation," they're not
having a conversation at all.

00:03:28.210 --> 00:03:32.830
They're kind of glomming onto
us to get us to almost support

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:34.980
their fragile selves.

00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:40.020
So if you, when you're
alone, are constantly

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.750
going to your phone
instead of being

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:46.640
able to tolerate that moment
of gathering yourself,

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:54.580
that's a kind of wake-up
call for you to make sure

00:03:54.580 --> 00:04:00.280
that you're comfortable with
who you are and have cultivated

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:01.860
this capacity for solitude.

00:04:01.860 --> 00:04:05.820
And recent research
is not happy research.

00:04:05.820 --> 00:04:08.200
I mean, part of why
I wrote this book is

00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:12.874
that recent research on solitude
and conversation is chilling.

00:04:12.874 --> 00:04:14.790
There's this study that
shows that if you just

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:19.339
ask college students to
sit in a chair without--

00:04:19.339 --> 00:04:22.660
and this is not my research,
but I'm reporting research.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.340
You ask them to sit in
a chair without a phone,

00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:28.160
without a book, and
say, we're going

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:30.322
to ask you to do this
for 6 to 15 minutes.

00:04:30.322 --> 00:04:31.280
Are you good with that?

00:04:31.280 --> 00:04:32.480
They say, sure.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:34.230
Then you say, well,
we're going to ask you

00:04:34.230 --> 00:04:36.420
to do this for 6 to 15 minutes.

00:04:36.420 --> 00:04:39.160
Do you think that you'd want to
give yourself an electroshock

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:41.000
during that time?

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:43.770
They say, uh, I don't think so!

00:04:43.770 --> 00:04:48.650
And they look as though
the researcher is crazy.

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:51.530
And then after six
minutes, they begin

00:04:51.530 --> 00:04:56.290
to self-administer electroshocks
rather than just sit quietly

00:04:56.290 --> 00:04:57.870
with their own thoughts.

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:03.980
And this actually is
borne out in my research.

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:07.710
I do research at
stop signs, where

00:05:07.710 --> 00:05:10.460
that's like a three-second,
four-second stop.

00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:13.400
People pull out a
phone at a stop sign.

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:16.225
They will not sit at a stop
sign without pulling out a phone

00:05:16.225 --> 00:05:18.640
to check what's happening.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:23.100
So perhaps enough said.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:24.530
But there is a question.

00:05:24.530 --> 00:05:26.310
Of course, in
"Reclaiming Conversation"

00:05:26.310 --> 00:05:29.240
I go on and on about
how people talk

00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:33.960
about their incapacity, their
anxiety about being alone

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:38.170
with their thoughts, and how
they want to fill that space up

00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:41.060
with what's on their phone,
and what that anxiety

00:05:41.060 --> 00:05:42.830
is about, and so forth.

00:05:42.830 --> 00:05:44.970
So I actually think that
reclaiming conversation,

00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:50.120
reclaiming relationship, does
begin with reclaiming ourselves

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:51.360
in solitude.

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:55.010
And this kind of false
dichotomy between,

00:05:55.010 --> 00:05:58.790
oh, give it to Sherry
that we're together, OK,

00:05:58.790 --> 00:06:01.844
we should lighten up with the
phone, but when we're alone,

00:06:01.844 --> 00:06:03.260
it's none of her
business, I think

00:06:03.260 --> 00:06:05.632
I'd like to break that down.

00:06:05.632 --> 00:06:06.340
LOGAN URY: Great.

00:06:06.340 --> 00:06:08.930
On a related note, the book
emphasizes the importance

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:10.789
of boredom, especially
for children.

00:06:10.789 --> 00:06:11.580
SHERRY TURKLE: Yes.

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:14.320
LOGAN URY: Can you talk a bit
about what comes out of boredom

00:06:14.320 --> 00:06:15.940
and why it's so important?

00:06:15.940 --> 00:06:20.860
SHERRY TURKLE: Well,
neurophysiologically, a lot's

00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:24.970
going on in boredom that is not
boring for your brain at all.

00:06:24.970 --> 00:06:28.890
Boredom is the time when your
brain is actually establishing

00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:31.230
what's called the default
mode network, which

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:36.470
is the brain's sense of its
stable, autobiographical self.

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:43.220
So in those moments of downtime,
your brain is very busy indeed.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:46.780
And again, if your idea
of a moment of boredom

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:51.820
is an opportunity to fill in
with the feed on your phone,

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:56.690
you're depriving your brain
of something it really needs.

00:06:56.690 --> 00:07:00.040
Beyond that, boredom
is considered

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:03.260
by most psychologists
to be one of the signal

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:05.430
achievements of childhood.

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:11.600
The capacity to be bored
and let your mind wander

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:16.820
is your imagination
calling to you to go inward

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:22.070
rather than to turn outward to
a phone or some other device.

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:28.960
Which is why somebody like
me is so concerned with baby

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:32.600
bouncers that have
slots for an iPad,

00:07:32.600 --> 00:07:39.090
with potty trainers that
have slots for an iPad.

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:44.110
These things were either moments
where a caretaker and a child

00:07:44.110 --> 00:07:49.250
should have been allowed to
engage in the beginnings of eye

00:07:49.250 --> 00:07:51.810
contact, communication,
conversation,

00:07:51.810 --> 00:07:54.820
or they're moments for reverie.

00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:59.700
And to think that these are
minutes for screen stimulation

00:07:59.700 --> 00:08:04.084
again is robbing us of
an important moment.

00:08:04.084 --> 00:08:06.250
LOGAN URY: Another key theme
in the book is empathy.

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:08.320
And you mention
that a meta study

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:12.040
found a 40% decrease in
empathy in college students

00:08:12.040 --> 00:08:13.840
over the past 20 years.

00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:15.390
You also mention
that kids who spend

00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:18.460
five days at a device-free camp
displayed much more empathy

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:19.529
than a control group.

00:08:19.529 --> 00:08:21.320
What can you tell us
about the relationship

00:08:21.320 --> 00:08:22.881
between technology and empathy?

00:08:22.881 --> 00:08:24.630
SHERRY TURKLE: Well,
I would say that this

00:08:24.630 --> 00:08:26.760
is the sort of
leitmotif of the book,

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:31.210
is this kind of empathy
crisis, because I was brought

00:08:31.210 --> 00:08:35.730
in to studying the book
when I was asked to consult

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.370
by middle schools
about what teachers

00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:43.409
felt were disturbing patterns
in middle school students.

00:08:43.409 --> 00:08:48.950
Which I wouldn't have
known from my own life

00:08:48.950 --> 00:08:51.350
as an MIT professor.

00:08:51.350 --> 00:08:54.020
What I knew from my
life as an MIT professor

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:57.970
is that students didn't want
to come to office hours.

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:02.520
Students want to
send in an email

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:07.750
and compose a perfect
question, and have

00:09:07.750 --> 00:09:11.280
me write them back
a perfect answer,

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:18.855
a kind of transactional model of
what goes on with a professor.

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:25.230
And I didn't have
reason to think it was

00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:27.260
because they lacked empathy.

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:30.710
What I knew is that
they didn't know

00:09:30.710 --> 00:09:33.800
the work that
conversation can do

00:09:33.800 --> 00:09:36.150
in terms of sparking learning.

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:39.330
Because nobody who loves
learning or who grew up to be

00:09:39.330 --> 00:09:43.200
a professor was because
they wrote a professor

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.920
a perfect letter and got
a perfect letter back.

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:48.520
It was because, on
the contrary, they

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:50.410
didn't have a perfect letter.

00:09:50.410 --> 00:09:52.270
They came in with
nothing, or little,

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.660
and somebody said, well,
that's not very good,

00:09:54.660 --> 00:09:58.950
but I'm going to stick with
you because I care about you.

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.900
Come back, and
we'll work on this.

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:03.330
It wasn't because
they wrote a perfect

00:10:03.330 --> 00:10:05.190
and got a perfect return.

00:10:05.190 --> 00:10:11.150
So I noticed a kind of lack,
a kind of transactional idea

00:10:11.150 --> 00:10:14.225
about what a conversation was.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:21.720
But then I was asked to
do this consulting work

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:24.100
in middle schools,
where teachers

00:10:24.100 --> 00:10:31.710
were observing a lack of
empathy among younger kids.

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:35.390
And we're used to thinking
of cyberbullying as well.

00:10:35.390 --> 00:10:38.050
People don't see the face.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:40.890
And so, OK, they
cyberbullied because the face

00:10:40.890 --> 00:10:43.230
isn't called up,
which is what calls up

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:45.100
the sort of moral
response in us.

00:10:45.100 --> 00:10:46.540
Philosophers have
been telling us

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:48.780
that for years, that
it's the face that

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:53.190
calls up our moral selves.

00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:55.055
But now psychology
is teaching us

00:10:55.055 --> 00:10:59.700
that it's actually the lack of
a face, the lack of an identity,

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:02.920
is what causes this
online-- I call it

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:06.900
a sort of disinhibition
that leads to cyberbullying.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:11.320
But now you're seeing that among
kids in face-to-face behavior.

00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:18.870
The way one teacher put
it, that 12-year-olds play

00:11:18.870 --> 00:11:20.890
on the playground
like 8-year-olds,

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:25.110
that they'll exclude a child,
and then they can't imagine,

00:11:25.110 --> 00:11:27.930
they can't put themselves
in the place of that child.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.760
They're not able to do
what empathy requires,

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:36.780
which is to put themselves
in the place of.

00:11:36.780 --> 00:11:43.430
And the teachers began to
talk about that in one school.

00:11:43.430 --> 00:11:47.860
And in their mind, it had to do
with the way these kids weren't

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:52.580
talking to each other, but
were really almost all the time

00:11:52.580 --> 00:11:55.300
talking to each other
through their phones.

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:58.770
So in the lunchroom, their
way of talking to each other

00:11:58.770 --> 00:12:03.000
was to take out their phones
and show each other what

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:04.400
was on their phones.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.830
And in fact, when I went to
camps, these device-free camps

00:12:07.830 --> 00:12:10.930
where the empathy
level goes way back up,

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:13.460
I think because kids
talk to each other

00:12:13.460 --> 00:12:17.140
and get this practice in putting
yourself in the other person's

00:12:17.140 --> 00:12:22.730
place-- I don't think this is
complicated-- the kids said

00:12:22.730 --> 00:12:25.800
that what was different between
their relationships at camp

00:12:25.800 --> 00:12:29.000
and at home was that
they spoke to each other,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.940
not about what's on
their phones but what

00:12:31.940 --> 00:12:33.940
was just happening at camp.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:39.650
So there were signs from a lot
of different places and spaces

00:12:39.650 --> 00:12:44.610
that there was something
up with empathy.

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:51.360
And since the early days
of working on this book,

00:12:51.360 --> 00:12:54.900
this empathy gap has
certainly become a major theme

00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:58.460
both in my work and
throughout the research

00:12:58.460 --> 00:12:59.980
literature in psychology.

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:04.020
I will say that I recently just
spent a day with the woman who

00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:10.080
did the study showing the 40%
decline in the past 20 years

00:13:10.080 --> 00:13:12.900
among college students,
big empathy drop.

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:19.160
And she is developing
empathy apps for the iPhone.

00:13:19.160 --> 00:13:24.620
And I think that's where
I'd love, in a Q&amp;A,

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:26.360
to hear your thoughts.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:32.750
I mean, because here
we are at a place where

00:13:32.750 --> 00:13:39.190
it's not out of line to think
of you developing empathy apps.

00:13:39.190 --> 00:13:45.840
And clearly I think of
us as the empathy app.

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:51.980
We are the empathy app, since
the way we develop empathy

00:13:51.980 --> 00:13:53.470
is to talk to each other.

00:13:57.110 --> 00:14:00.510
But I'm not closed
at all to the idea

00:14:00.510 --> 00:14:08.350
of using technology to help
us in reclaiming empathy.

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:14.380
But my first instinct is,
we are the empathy app.

00:14:14.380 --> 00:14:15.680
We need to talk to each other.

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:19.710
We need to talk to
our kids, that somehow

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:22.300
putting a baby in a baby bouncer
and putting a screen that

00:14:22.300 --> 00:14:24.790
has an empathy app
in front of this baby

00:14:24.790 --> 00:14:29.780
instead of putting
you-- and yet I

00:14:29.780 --> 00:14:31.960
felt for her that
she was so upset

00:14:31.960 --> 00:14:33.340
when she got this response.

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:38.030
She got this result. She
wanted to do something.

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:40.640
And I think that that's part of
one of the themes of the book,

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:45.010
is that it's not
anti-technology.

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:47.140
It's pro-conversation,
that sometimes we

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:53.260
just need to know when to
be there for each other.

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:54.750
So anyway, that's
my empathy story.

00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:58.030
Clearly I'm-- oh, and also,
what's the difference between

00:14:58.030 --> 00:15:01.196
empathy and compassion?

00:15:01.196 --> 00:15:02.570
Since the book
came out-- I mean,

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:04.720
really I wrote it to
spark a conversation

00:15:04.720 --> 00:15:06.470
about conversation.

00:15:06.470 --> 00:15:08.310
There's been a lot
of talk about, well,

00:15:08.310 --> 00:15:11.140
empathy isn't as
important as compassion.

00:15:11.140 --> 00:15:13.710
I mean, look at all the
stuff we learned about places

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:17.720
all over the world because
we have the internet.

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:19.340
Now maybe the
important thing we have

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:23.640
is compassion for all these
things we don't know about,

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:26.790
and maybe empathy is
a little old-school.

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:30.487
So I'm here to say I don't
think empathy is old-school.

00:15:30.487 --> 00:15:32.070
LOGAN URY: So now I
want to transition

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:33.710
a bit into talking about--

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:33.980
SHERRY TURKLE: Romance.

00:15:33.980 --> 00:15:35.063
LOGAN URY: Modern romance.

00:15:35.063 --> 00:15:37.250
So in the book, you
mention that the sight

00:15:37.250 --> 00:15:39.950
of a phone on a table,
even if it's silent,

00:15:39.950 --> 00:15:43.720
even if it turns over, worsens
the quality of the conversation

00:15:43.720 --> 00:15:45.749
and makes it less empathetic.

00:15:45.749 --> 00:15:46.540
SHERRY TURKLE: Yes.

00:15:46.540 --> 00:15:48.831
LOGAN URY: So I'm definitely
going to take that advice.

00:15:48.831 --> 00:15:51.670
I was wondering what other
advice you have for people here

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:53.900
who feel like
technology is getting

00:15:53.900 --> 00:15:56.314
in the way of their
romantic connections.

00:15:56.314 --> 00:15:58.105
SHERRY TURKLE: Well,
this study is amazing.

00:15:58.105 --> 00:16:02.550
I mean, if you just did one
thing, but not just in romance,

00:16:02.550 --> 00:16:04.300
in your families,
in your friendships,

00:16:04.300 --> 00:16:07.040
with your children,
with your everybody--

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:10.370
so just make sure you understand
the setup of this experiment.

00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:12.862
Take two people out to lunch.

00:16:12.862 --> 00:16:15.320
Obviously you don't tell them
what the experiment is about.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:16.900
You feed them their lunch.

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:21.510
On the table, there's a phone
turned off and turned over.

00:16:21.510 --> 00:16:23.200
And you're measuring
their conversation

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:27.500
against a control
group with no phone.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:29.980
Just the silent
phone on the table

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:34.200
will cause the conversation to
go to truly trivial matters.

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:37.720
And the people will report
less of a sense of connection

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:40.680
with each other, less of a
sense of caring about each other

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:44.160
or of understanding what's
on the other person's mind--

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:45.770
just the presence of that phone.

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.400
So they re-did the study.

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:49.890
I mean, it was such
an amazing study.

00:16:49.890 --> 00:16:55.340
They re-did the study
in a natural setting.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:16:58.500
Forget the laboratory and giving
people lunch in a laboratory.

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:01.170
In a natural setting
like a shopping mall,

00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:04.700
and they just put the
phones on the periphery

00:17:04.700 --> 00:17:06.790
of people's vision--
I mean, like

00:17:06.790 --> 00:17:09.190
at the edge of people's vision.

00:17:09.190 --> 00:17:13.079
And again they found that even
a silent phone disconnects us.

00:17:13.079 --> 00:17:17.740
So the most important
thing you can do on a date,

00:17:17.740 --> 00:17:21.010
or on a breakfast,
or at a lunch,

00:17:21.010 --> 00:17:26.670
or at a business meeting, or at
an anything where your goal is

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:32.630
to have the conversation
not degrade to trivialities,

00:17:32.630 --> 00:17:35.050
to maybe make an empathic
connection, like maybe

00:17:35.050 --> 00:17:37.380
like a second date
where somebody-- or more

00:17:37.380 --> 00:17:40.120
than that, the first
step in falling in love

00:17:40.120 --> 00:17:42.910
has to be that somebody
feels that something big is

00:17:42.910 --> 00:17:46.866
at stake-- is put
away your phone.

00:17:46.866 --> 00:17:48.490
It's not enough to
turn off your phone.

00:17:48.490 --> 00:17:49.840
Put away your phone.

00:17:49.840 --> 00:17:53.190
Because a phone reminds
us, whether or not

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:56.720
we want it to
remind us, that you

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:58.980
have the capacity
to be elsewhere.

00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:01.490
It's not even that you
want to be elsewhere,

00:18:01.490 --> 00:18:04.590
but that you have the
capacity to be elsewhere.

00:18:04.590 --> 00:18:10.440
So I think that before I go
on to other Turkle tips--

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:14.390
because I must say that
the research on this book--

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:18.350
and a whole chapter
is on romance--

00:18:18.350 --> 00:18:23.894
I'm surprisingly filled
with tips and advice.

00:18:23.894 --> 00:18:26.670
And the book was reviewed by
Jonathan Franzen in the "New

00:18:26.670 --> 00:18:29.230
York Times," and he
described it as in part

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:31.570
a kind of like
totally high-class

00:18:31.570 --> 00:18:32.840
academic self-help book.

00:18:32.840 --> 00:18:36.380
And I couldn't figure out if
that was like good or bad.

00:18:36.380 --> 00:18:38.766
LOGAN URY: I wanted
to ask you about that.

00:18:38.766 --> 00:18:40.140
SHERRY TURKLE: On
the one hand, I

00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:43.790
thought, kiss of death
with my colleagues,

00:18:43.790 --> 00:18:48.120
like people will never
again invite me to lunch.

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:53.810
And then I thought, well, after
investigating conversation

00:18:53.810 --> 00:18:56.950
and empathy, why
shouldn't I have

00:18:56.950 --> 00:18:59.590
written a book that actually
tells some people things

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:04.680
about how to be an
advocate for conversation?

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:06.580
So I decided to own it.

00:19:06.580 --> 00:19:10.820
So I'm OK with that.

00:19:10.820 --> 00:19:13.200
But that is the most
important thing you can do,

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:15.730
is really sacred spaces.

00:19:15.730 --> 00:19:16.730
Put away your phone.

00:19:16.730 --> 00:19:19.490
And then sacred spaces
for conversation--

00:19:19.490 --> 00:19:23.290
the dinner, the kitchen,
the dining room, the car.

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:26.080
The car.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:29.132
You're driving-- and I
was about to cross myself,

00:19:29.132 --> 00:19:30.090
even though I'm Jewish.

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:36.570
Really, it's not the place.

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:38.930
No devices.

00:19:38.930 --> 00:19:43.490
And if you're in a family,
you tell your family,

00:19:43.490 --> 00:19:46.680
we need to talk to each
other in this family.

00:19:46.680 --> 00:19:48.350
That's important to
me in our family,

00:19:48.350 --> 00:19:49.280
that we talk to each other.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:50.715
That's just how
it's going to be.

00:19:50.715 --> 00:19:54.120
It's easier to tell this to
somebody who's a younger child,

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:58.060
but an older child or a
boyfriend or girlfriend

00:19:58.060 --> 00:20:00.622
you can also tell.

00:20:00.622 --> 00:20:03.080
If you're sitting next to your
boyfriend-- you're driving--

00:20:03.080 --> 00:20:07.150
and he takes out his phone,
you say, it's important to me

00:20:07.150 --> 00:20:08.410
that we talk.

00:20:08.410 --> 00:20:12.590
And if he doesn't like
it, you just repeat.

00:20:12.590 --> 00:20:14.340
And then the same thing
if your girlfriend

00:20:14.340 --> 00:20:16.830
is using that as her time to
catch up on her social media

00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:17.990
feeds.

00:20:17.990 --> 00:20:20.190
Create a culture
in the car where

00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:22.050
that's a time for talking.

00:20:22.050 --> 00:20:23.630
And I think that's
very important.

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:26.170
A third tip, and
this is something

00:20:26.170 --> 00:20:33.770
that was so important in the
interviews I did on romance,

00:20:33.770 --> 00:20:38.650
was the-- I call it
the nothing gambit.

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:44.640
In romance, so often what you
get back in texting is nothing.

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:46.710
And people talk to me about it.

00:20:46.710 --> 00:20:49.670
They ask me, in
history, could you

00:20:49.670 --> 00:20:54.926
ever do that before, people
just dropping out like nothing?

00:20:54.926 --> 00:20:58.660
And, like, nothing?

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:07.100
And actually, people
could not call you back,

00:21:07.100 --> 00:21:08.590
but that's a little different.

00:21:08.590 --> 00:21:09.610
That's like a statement.

00:21:09.610 --> 00:21:12.360
That's saying, I'm
not calling you back.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:16.350
But it's not like in the middle
of a conversation-- I say this.

00:21:16.350 --> 00:21:17.230
You say this.

00:21:17.230 --> 00:21:18.472
I say this.

00:21:18.472 --> 00:21:20.400
[SILENCE]

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:25.910
And people actually experience
that quite differently,

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:29.180
as, the date ends.

00:21:29.180 --> 00:21:32.130
There's just nothing after.

00:21:32.130 --> 00:21:35.690
And people sort of say, well,
she didn't call me back.

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:38.280
He didn't call me back.

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:39.340
You could check.

00:21:39.340 --> 00:21:42.170
Some people check in to-- they
know they shouldn't, but they

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:42.670
do.

00:21:42.670 --> 00:21:45.600
But sometimes
there's a check-in,

00:21:45.600 --> 00:21:49.770
but people kind of know that
if there's a great quieting,

00:21:49.770 --> 00:21:51.380
they know what happened.

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:54.440
But it's almost as though the
human nervous system isn't

00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:58.370
set up for conversation in which
you say this, and I say this,

00:21:58.370 --> 00:22:04.800
and I say this, and-- and
people find it quite upsetting.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:08.540
And I would say that
it isn't a good way

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:14.260
to end your relationships
because it actually

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:19.070
causes distress and
disorientation, much

00:22:19.070 --> 00:22:20.940
more than you mean to cause.

00:22:20.940 --> 00:22:23.990
Because usually when people
are doing the nothing response,

00:22:23.990 --> 00:22:25.750
all they're doing
is they're deciding

00:22:25.750 --> 00:22:27.458
they really don't want
to go out anymore.

00:22:29.800 --> 00:22:32.307
It's really like
not calling back.

00:22:32.307 --> 00:22:33.973
But they're not
treating it like they're

00:22:33.973 --> 00:22:35.660
in the middle of a conversation.

00:22:35.660 --> 00:22:37.960
They're treating it
like they've had a date,

00:22:37.960 --> 00:22:40.460
and they don't want to call her
again to go on another date,

00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:42.550
or call him again.

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:45.560
But psychologically,
it's not like that.

00:22:45.560 --> 00:22:48.680
LOGAN URY: So what
should people do instead?

00:22:48.680 --> 00:22:51.830
SHERRY TURKLE: Well, the
best thing to do is say--

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:54.085
and this is the thing
that no one wants to do,

00:22:54.085 --> 00:22:55.710
but again, it's to
have a conversation,

00:22:55.710 --> 00:22:57.850
like I loved our date.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:01.500
It was so fun, and I just loved
going to the [? Gotzengould ?]

00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:02.000
opera.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:08.320
It was amazing that you
thought to invite me there.

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:10.160
We share so little.

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:11.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:12.310 --> 00:23:16.640
But in business, there's
this ridiculous--

00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:18.760
when you have a
manuscript turned down,

00:23:18.760 --> 00:23:23.820
or I don't know how many of you
have submitted film scripts,

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:26.210
there's this new
line, we've decided

00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:27.860
to go in another direction.

00:23:27.860 --> 00:23:29.650
Have you heard this?

00:23:29.650 --> 00:23:31.330
Have you heard this
line, we've decided

00:23:31.330 --> 00:23:32.830
to go in another direction?

00:23:32.830 --> 00:23:35.660
It's actually a very
interesting line

00:23:35.660 --> 00:23:38.737
because it basically doesn't
say your thing is bad.

00:23:38.737 --> 00:23:40.820
It says, we've decided to
go in another direction.

00:23:40.820 --> 00:23:43.270
You just say, you know,
I really had a good time,

00:23:43.270 --> 00:23:46.330
but I think this just
isn't right for me.

00:23:46.330 --> 00:23:48.860
And it's the functional
equivalent of,

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:50.884
I decided to go in
another direction.

00:23:50.884 --> 00:23:52.300
Which the first
time I heard it, I

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:54.230
thought, oh, this
is so pretentious.

00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:58.270
It must have been
invented in California.

00:23:58.270 --> 00:24:01.460
But actually I've
come to appreciate it.

00:24:01.460 --> 00:24:04.140
I've just come to appreciate
it because I think it actually

00:24:04.140 --> 00:24:09.020
is very honest.

00:24:09.020 --> 00:24:10.730
I mean, it actually is kind.

00:24:10.730 --> 00:24:14.430
It's saying, I'm going--
it's accurate in some sort

00:24:14.430 --> 00:24:18.600
of bizarre-- it's like, I'm
going in another direction.

00:24:18.600 --> 00:24:22.600
So the kindest thing is
to just actually complete

00:24:22.600 --> 00:24:23.920
the conversation.

00:24:23.920 --> 00:24:25.420
I'm going in another direction.

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:28.630
Which is what you say
when you say that I think

00:24:28.630 --> 00:24:30.700
that this isn't right for me.

00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:32.450
I like "it isn't right for me."

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:35.980
Continuing on a romantic
basis isn't right for me.

00:24:35.980 --> 00:24:38.712
So that's my love tip.

00:24:38.712 --> 00:24:40.170
LOGAN URY: We'll
check on your mic.

00:24:40.170 --> 00:24:42.610
On a related note, one of
the most memorable stories

00:24:42.610 --> 00:24:45.290
in your book, and Aziz Ansari
also put this in his book

00:24:45.290 --> 00:24:47.020
from your research,
was the story

00:24:47.020 --> 00:24:49.100
of a young man
who had a standing

00:24:49.100 --> 00:24:51.180
date with his grandparents
to have dinner there.

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:53.060
And when he wanted
to cancel, he just

00:24:53.060 --> 00:24:55.915
wanted to send them a text or an
email to say he couldn't come.

00:24:55.915 --> 00:24:57.200
And his mom said no.

00:24:57.200 --> 00:25:00.354
SHERRY TURKLE: So did Aziz
quote me, or did I quote Aziz?

00:25:00.354 --> 00:25:01.770
LOGAN URY: Aziz
quoted you, right?

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:02.706
SHERRY TURKLE: Yeah.

00:25:02.706 --> 00:25:04.285
LOGAN URY: Yeah, OK.

00:25:04.285 --> 00:25:06.910
SHERRY TURKLE: Because Aziz and
I worked together for a minute.

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:07.940
It could have been either.

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:08.960
LOGAN URY: I think
it's your research.

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:09.793
SHERRY TURKLE: Yeah.

00:25:09.793 --> 00:25:12.990
LOGAN URY: So the mom said, you
have to call your grandparents.

00:25:12.990 --> 00:25:15.695
And in calling the grandparents,
he heard the disappointment

00:25:15.695 --> 00:25:16.320
in their voice.

00:25:16.320 --> 00:25:17.694
They had already
started cooking.

00:25:17.694 --> 00:25:18.660
They had set the table.

00:25:18.660 --> 00:25:20.042
And it was much
harder to cancel.

00:25:20.042 --> 00:25:22.000
And I just thought that
was so profound because

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:25.610
of not only how people break
up, but just general flakiness.

00:25:25.610 --> 00:25:27.407
So maybe you can talk
a bit about that.

00:25:27.407 --> 00:25:29.490
But I thought that was
just such a good tip, which

00:25:29.490 --> 00:25:32.700
is if you want to
cancel plans, you

00:25:32.700 --> 00:25:34.430
should suffer the
consequences of knowing

00:25:34.430 --> 00:25:35.660
how it affects the person.

00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:38.230
SHERRY TURKLE: Well, this has
also to do with apologizing.

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:43.540
What was nice about
this story was

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:46.910
that it came upon very
naturally in the family.

00:25:46.910 --> 00:25:51.420
So this was the
mother's parents--

00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:55.710
and they lived very close--
would invite the son over

00:25:55.710 --> 00:25:59.290
to-- I think he was 11-- would
invite him over to dinner.

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:02.720
And it wasn't like Thanksgiving.

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:04.240
This wasn't Rosh Hashanah.

00:26:04.240 --> 00:26:08.900
I mean, it was just like,
come over to dinner.

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:10.800
And as he got a
little bit older,

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:14.330
because it wasn't like a
big holiday or something,

00:26:14.330 --> 00:26:16.670
he just got preoccupied
with other things.

00:26:16.670 --> 00:26:19.460
And this thing settled in
where because he didn't

00:26:19.460 --> 00:26:24.360
have to see them, he could
just type, I'm sorry,

00:26:24.360 --> 00:26:27.710
can't come, and hit Send.

00:26:27.710 --> 00:26:32.890
And it really was not
good for the family.

00:26:32.890 --> 00:26:41.120
And he was not feeling that
he was causing distress.

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:46.090
And the mother just decided that
he had to at least call them

00:26:46.090 --> 00:26:49.830
because when he
called, he got to hear,

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:55.430
your grandfather went to get
sundaes with caramel sauce,

00:26:55.430 --> 00:27:00.250
and he got all the toppings,
like you do a sundae bar.

00:27:00.250 --> 00:27:01.822
There's a roast in the oven.

00:27:01.822 --> 00:27:03.530
I'm making your favorite
russet potatoes.

00:27:03.530 --> 00:27:05.860
I mean, he got to hear
that actually they

00:27:05.860 --> 00:27:08.360
were going to have this dinner
anyway, the grandfather liked

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:10.550
the caramel sauce
anyway, that it wasn't as

00:27:10.550 --> 00:27:13.320
though these people were
incompetent and dependent

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:15.470
and were going to fall apart.

00:27:15.470 --> 00:27:17.680
But he was going to be missed.

00:27:17.680 --> 00:27:21.350
And I think that that's
what you don't get with,

00:27:21.350 --> 00:27:22.660
I'm sorry, and hit Send.

00:27:22.660 --> 00:27:25.260
Because the dance of what
happens in an apology--

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:29.260
I mean, take it to the higher
level for romantic purposes.

00:27:29.260 --> 00:27:30.935
An apology is so important.

00:27:30.935 --> 00:27:34.650
And in my book, I
interview a woman

00:27:34.650 --> 00:27:37.920
who says, if my boyfriend
apologizes by phone,

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:41.170
I know 100% of the
time that we are

00:27:41.170 --> 00:27:43.300
going to go back
over this again,

00:27:43.300 --> 00:27:46.400
because none of the work
of an apology gets done.

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:52.400
Because in an apology, I get to
see-- I'm apologizing to you.

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:54.860
I get to see that you're upset.

00:27:54.860 --> 00:27:58.820
Then you get to
see that I'm upset.

00:27:58.820 --> 00:28:01.020
And so you soften.

00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:04.120
You think, OK, she's really--
my grandmother used to say,

00:28:04.120 --> 00:28:06.520
don't apologize until
you're contrite enough,

00:28:06.520 --> 00:28:08.090
or it's not going to work.

00:28:08.090 --> 00:28:09.490
Hold off.

00:28:09.490 --> 00:28:11.560
Think about it
until you mean it,

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:13.190
or else it's not going to work.

00:28:13.190 --> 00:28:15.560
An apology is not
saying I'm sorry.

00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:18.150
You have to have this
whole dance go on.

00:28:18.150 --> 00:28:21.750
So then you see I'm really
upset, and you soften.

00:28:21.750 --> 00:28:23.820
What, you can't
make eye contact?

00:28:23.820 --> 00:28:24.779
[LAUGHTER]

00:28:24.779 --> 00:28:26.320
AUDIENCE: I didn't
do anything wrong.

00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:28.430
SHERRY TURKLE: No, no, no, look.

00:28:28.430 --> 00:28:29.850
But you see how hard it is?

00:28:29.850 --> 00:28:35.990
Because then you have to
see that I really feel bad.

00:28:35.990 --> 00:28:38.760
It's hard, because then you
have to see I really feel bad.

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:41.970
And then I see, ah,
I have an opening.

00:28:41.970 --> 00:28:44.480
Now you can break
our eye contact.

00:28:44.480 --> 00:28:51.300
I have an opening that I can
make something happen here.

00:28:51.300 --> 00:28:54.950
But unless I see
that he-- the reason

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:57.280
I was disoriented
when he looked away

00:28:57.280 --> 00:28:59.320
is because I was actually
trying to put myself

00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:00.740
into that state of mind.

00:29:00.740 --> 00:29:04.890
Do I have an opening with this
guy where if I say I'm sorry,

00:29:04.890 --> 00:29:07.310
we can move to something else?

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:11.550
And that's a whole
complicated dance

00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:14.490
of people learning empathy.

00:29:14.490 --> 00:29:16.860
And if you don't do that,
if you don't teach that,

00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:20.860
if you don't model that, if
you don't learn all of that,

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:23.920
you're missing a lot.

00:29:23.920 --> 00:29:29.295
In a romantic context, that's
sort of back to basics.

00:29:29.295 --> 00:29:31.420
I mean, people are hurting
each other all the time.

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:34.470
I mean, there's no way to have
a close relationship in which

00:29:34.470 --> 00:29:35.550
you're not having bumps.

00:29:35.550 --> 00:29:37.120
If you're not
having bumps, you're

00:29:37.120 --> 00:29:38.734
not in a close relationship.

00:29:38.734 --> 00:29:40.400
I mean, it's almost
you put it that way,

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:42.577
that it's not just like
in a close relationship,

00:29:42.577 --> 00:29:44.160
there are obviously
going to be bumps.

00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:45.535
But if there aren't
bumps, you're

00:29:45.535 --> 00:29:47.130
not in a close relationship.

00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:53.880
So being able to
have ways of saying,

00:29:53.880 --> 00:29:57.070
hey, what I did
wasn't cool, or hey,

00:29:57.070 --> 00:29:59.510
I can understand
how you felt there,

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:02.000
that becomes part of the
dance of the relationship.

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:04.410
And if you're not doing
that face to face,

00:30:04.410 --> 00:30:08.270
the balance of things
isn't going to work.

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:12.066
So I would not use
texting for that purpose.

00:30:12.066 --> 00:30:13.690
LOGAN URY: So that's
a great transition

00:30:13.690 --> 00:30:16.014
into my next question,
which is about eye contact.

00:30:16.014 --> 00:30:18.430
And I thought a lot about this
as I was reading your book,

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:20.100
and now as I'm talking to you.

00:30:20.100 --> 00:30:22.380
And it just seems
like eye contact

00:30:22.380 --> 00:30:26.680
is such a key part of exchanging
information and a developing

00:30:26.680 --> 00:30:27.290
connection.

00:30:27.290 --> 00:30:28.750
And a few months
ago, this article

00:30:28.750 --> 00:30:31.970
came out about 36 questions
that lead to love.

00:30:31.970 --> 00:30:34.950
And it ends with people
staring into each other's eyes

00:30:34.950 --> 00:30:36.400
for four minutes.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:38.566
So I think as we're going
through Turkle tips,

00:30:38.566 --> 00:30:40.690
we should think a little
bit more about eye contact

00:30:40.690 --> 00:30:42.665
and really what it
can do for intimacy.

00:30:42.665 --> 00:30:43.540
SHERRY TURKLE: Right.

00:30:43.540 --> 00:30:46.940
Well, obviously eye
contact is so important.

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:51.960
And that's why
really I want people

00:30:51.960 --> 00:30:56.640
to think so hard about
screens in front of kids

00:30:56.640 --> 00:30:59.910
during moments when parents
used to look at them.

00:30:59.910 --> 00:31:04.080
I have a very close colleague
at MIT, Cynthia Breazeal,

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:09.230
who's developing robots
that will read to children.

00:31:09.230 --> 00:31:13.570
And I certainly get the gist.

00:31:16.395 --> 00:31:19.170
They will learn more
words, socioeconomic groups

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:20.810
that don't have words.

00:31:20.810 --> 00:31:31.090
But really, money for people
who would be with those kids

00:31:31.090 --> 00:31:36.025
and read to them-- I mean,
a half-million dollars

00:31:36.025 --> 00:31:38.700
to have some people
reading to those kids

00:31:38.700 --> 00:31:41.330
so they could make eye contact.

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:43.480
I really worry about that,
that they would actually

00:31:43.480 --> 00:31:47.010
develop something that people
will put in their homes

00:31:47.010 --> 00:31:49.590
so they can do their
email, and the robot

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:50.870
will read to the children.

00:31:50.870 --> 00:31:53.900
I really worry about
this, or the idea

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:58.590
of putting a baby bouncer
and having an activity,

00:31:58.590 --> 00:32:01.640
this slot for a pad.

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:07.195
Because eye contact is so
crucial for developmentally,

00:32:07.195 --> 00:32:09.770
and it's so crucial
in every relationship.

00:32:09.770 --> 00:32:15.990
And Skyping is so
interesting because in order

00:32:15.990 --> 00:32:19.684
for-- let's say I'm
Skyping with you.

00:32:19.684 --> 00:32:22.092
No, actually him.

00:32:22.092 --> 00:32:23.760
LOGAN URY: You're next.

00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:27.596
SHERRY TURKLE: In order-- no,
now you have to look at me.

00:32:27.596 --> 00:32:29.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:31.550
In order to-- or
I'll Skype with him.

00:32:31.550 --> 00:32:33.370
He wants to.

00:32:33.370 --> 00:32:35.490
In order to Skype-- OK,
you don't want to Skype.

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:40.890
In order to Skype
with you, and for you

00:32:40.890 --> 00:32:45.730
to have the feeling that
I'm looking at you, which

00:32:45.730 --> 00:32:51.430
is crucial to me, let's say,
if I want you to bond with me,

00:32:51.430 --> 00:32:55.070
if I want you to feel the
full blast of my attention,

00:32:55.070 --> 00:32:57.340
I have to look at the camera.

00:32:57.340 --> 00:32:59.480
So I can't be
looking at anything

00:32:59.480 --> 00:33:04.350
happening in order to give you
the experience of I'm looking

00:33:04.350 --> 00:33:05.390
at you.

00:33:05.390 --> 00:33:10.680
Now, how effed up is that,
that I'm having no experience,

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:14.480
or I'm only pretending to
have an experience in order

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:19.470
to give you a fake experience
that I'm looking at you?

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:27.110
So Skyping is really
perfect for a couple.

00:33:27.110 --> 00:33:29.700
Bringing you to the romantic
thing, you're in love.

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:31.720
You're at a distance.

00:33:31.720 --> 00:33:32.530
You're in Chicago.

00:33:32.530 --> 00:33:33.870
She's in New York.

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:35.130
You're cooking dinner.

00:33:35.130 --> 00:33:36.680
You set up to Skype.

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:39.210
And as you're each cooking
dinner, you're on Skype,

00:33:39.210 --> 00:33:40.410
and you're chatting.

00:33:40.410 --> 00:33:43.320
And you have that
sense of co-presence,

00:33:43.320 --> 00:33:46.130
and you're seeing each other's
bodies as you both cook dinner.

00:33:46.130 --> 00:33:47.530
Fantastic.

00:33:47.530 --> 00:33:49.750
In different states
of undress or whatever

00:33:49.750 --> 00:33:53.060
you want, whatever
you want to do.

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:57.860
But that's what
it's optimized for.

00:33:57.860 --> 00:34:03.785
It is not the place to do this.

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:10.510
And I've found, studying
different kinds of conference

00:34:10.510 --> 00:34:15.630
calling where theoretically the
camera situation is much more

00:34:15.630 --> 00:34:19.250
diffuse, so you should be able
to have that feeling of looking

00:34:19.250 --> 00:34:23.580
in each other's eyes,
is also very complicated

00:34:23.580 --> 00:34:29.120
because there comes a point
where somebody feels they're

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:31.870
in the main room
and some other group

00:34:31.870 --> 00:34:34.106
feels they're not
in the main room.

00:34:34.106 --> 00:34:35.730
And it usually
happens-- sometimes it's

00:34:35.730 --> 00:34:37.674
not clear where the main
room is going to be.

00:34:37.674 --> 00:34:39.590
There's like a little
bit of a power struggle,

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:41.110
like who's in the main room?

00:34:41.110 --> 00:34:44.699
And then something happens,
some subtle shift, and some room

00:34:44.699 --> 00:34:47.892
becomes the main room and some
room becomes not the main room.

00:34:47.892 --> 00:34:50.100
And then the people who are
not in the main room, who

00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:53.639
decide that they're not in
the main room, start to text.

00:34:53.639 --> 00:34:56.530
And sometimes they start
to text under the table,

00:34:56.530 --> 00:34:59.376
which is called phubbing.

00:34:59.376 --> 00:35:00.750
And my students
tell me they know

00:35:00.750 --> 00:35:03.470
how to do this, that they all
learned it in middle school

00:35:03.470 --> 00:35:09.510
when they wanted to text, and
not be seen by their teachers.

00:35:09.510 --> 00:35:12.500
So sometimes you see people
doing it under the table,

00:35:12.500 --> 00:35:15.700
and then sometimes, as though
they aren't being seen,

00:35:15.700 --> 00:35:18.630
they'll just be doing it right
there because they're not

00:35:18.630 --> 00:35:19.700
in the main room.

00:35:19.700 --> 00:35:23.590
So again, it has its place.

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:24.600
You're a global company.

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:25.480
You have to do it.

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:29.980
But it's more
like, have respect.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:34.010
My message is, have
respect for this thing

00:35:34.010 --> 00:35:36.420
that we know how to do
humanly, and it definitely

00:35:36.420 --> 00:35:37.300
has its place.

00:35:37.300 --> 00:35:40.400
And do it when you can,
and respect its power

00:35:40.400 --> 00:35:42.470
when you get a chance to do it.

00:35:42.470 --> 00:35:47.270
And in romance, I tell
a story of a couple who

00:35:47.270 --> 00:35:58.110
choose-- this is this Adam and
Tessa couple who actually like

00:35:58.110 --> 00:36:01.780
screen stuff
because, particularly

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:07.190
on the part of the guy, he
feels that he can be a better

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:11.340
self when he is online.

00:36:11.340 --> 00:36:12.820
More empathic.

00:36:12.820 --> 00:36:14.270
He can edit himself.

00:36:14.270 --> 00:36:16.010
He can get it right.

00:36:16.010 --> 00:36:18.990
I'm not going to ask for a
show of hands, but all of us

00:36:18.990 --> 00:36:25.122
have had the feeling that--
I sometimes get angry.

00:36:25.122 --> 00:36:28.660
You wouldn't believe that, but
I sometimes can get very angry.

00:36:28.660 --> 00:36:30.890
And I have that
bitch-- that kind of

00:36:30.890 --> 00:36:33.800
like just angry response.

00:36:33.800 --> 00:36:40.114
And then online, I'm just, oh,
that's a kind of funny thing

00:36:40.114 --> 00:36:40.905
to have had happen.

00:36:44.230 --> 00:36:45.930
I'm a better person.

00:36:45.930 --> 00:36:47.584
I can just have that
moment, and then I

00:36:47.584 --> 00:36:49.000
don't have to show
it because I've

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.950
had that delay time to edit.

00:36:51.950 --> 00:36:55.830
So we've all had that experience
of feeling like the better me

00:36:55.830 --> 00:36:57.430
gets to be the one online.

00:36:57.430 --> 00:37:00.060
So the guy in the
relationship, Adam,

00:37:00.060 --> 00:37:04.060
really likes that, feels
that he is the better himself

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:06.575
in the online presentation.

00:37:06.575 --> 00:37:09.650
And he's with a woman, Tessa,
who basically is telling him

00:37:09.650 --> 00:37:13.600
that he's not empathic enough
throughout the relationship.

00:37:13.600 --> 00:37:15.360
I mean, she ultimately
breaks up with him

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:17.485
because she's telling him
he's not empathic enough.

00:37:17.485 --> 00:37:21.810
I mean, even online, even with
all these efforts after three

00:37:21.810 --> 00:37:25.820
years, he hasn't reached
her empathy standard.

00:37:25.820 --> 00:37:35.960
So love tip-- you are the self.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:40.860
You can edit online
and be-- it's

00:37:40.860 --> 00:37:47.564
good to be a more-- when you're
with people you care about,

00:37:47.564 --> 00:37:49.230
and with people who
are working for you,

00:37:49.230 --> 00:37:53.390
when with your loved ones,
nothing wrong about being

00:37:53.390 --> 00:37:55.660
online and not having
that immediate bitch

00:37:55.660 --> 00:37:57.620
response that I sometimes get.

00:37:57.620 --> 00:38:00.220
You know, I'm overworked
and overstressed and running

00:38:00.220 --> 00:38:03.887
around, and somebody
does something

00:38:03.887 --> 00:38:05.470
which is going to
cost me three hours.

00:38:05.470 --> 00:38:07.620
And I'm like, are
you kidding me?

00:38:07.620 --> 00:38:10.350
That kind of response.

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:14.560
Nothing wrong with that, with
going online and suppressing

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:15.540
it.

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:20.700
But really let the people
you love see who you are.

00:38:23.500 --> 00:38:31.290
Because it is the unedited
you that you have to accept,

00:38:31.290 --> 00:38:34.550
that they have to accept,
that you have to work on,

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:37.650
and you have to feel loved for.

00:38:37.650 --> 00:38:43.120
And it works in romance,
but more dangerously.

00:38:43.120 --> 00:38:45.540
Parents-- again,
in the book, I talk

00:38:45.540 --> 00:38:49.080
about parents wanting their
children to talk to robots.

00:38:49.080 --> 00:38:52.740
And Hello Barbie or Siri--
Hello Barbie is a fancy one,

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:54.420
but all kinds of
sociable robots are

00:38:54.420 --> 00:38:56.990
being invented to
talk to children,

00:38:56.990 --> 00:39:01.210
to be their best friend,
to be their buddy.

00:39:01.210 --> 00:39:03.520
And I talk about, from
a psychological point

00:39:03.520 --> 00:39:07.250
of view, that danger lurks.

00:39:07.250 --> 00:39:09.425
Because one of the
messages the child--

00:39:09.425 --> 00:39:10.975
I mean, apart from
the fact that I

00:39:10.975 --> 00:39:14.250
think pretend empathy
is toxic, but that's

00:39:14.250 --> 00:39:18.020
such a different lecture that
I won't even get into it here.

00:39:18.020 --> 00:39:20.750
In the book, I go into
this in great detail.

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:24.570
But apart from that,
you have to let

00:39:24.570 --> 00:39:32.800
a child feel that their truth is
something that a parent can not

00:39:32.800 --> 00:39:35.260
only tolerate but love.

00:39:35.260 --> 00:39:39.730
And similarly, in romance,
at the end of the day,

00:39:39.730 --> 00:39:42.240
you have to feel that
the truth of who you are

00:39:42.240 --> 00:39:46.460
is what the person
you love can love.

00:39:46.460 --> 00:39:49.010
So that is a more
profound-- since we

00:39:49.010 --> 00:39:52.520
began on sort of putting
away your phone on a date,

00:39:52.520 --> 00:39:57.925
this moves us to the deepest
level of tips for romance,

00:39:57.925 --> 00:40:03.280
is you have to feel that the
person you're with actually

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:08.050
loves you, with all the
flaws, and loves who you are.

00:40:08.050 --> 00:40:11.730
And there's something about
this going online and editing

00:40:11.730 --> 00:40:15.017
yourself that can
interfere with that.

00:40:15.017 --> 00:40:16.270
LOGAN URY: Thank you.

