I mean, for six years I've done
nothing but interview people.

00:41:23.076 --> 00:41:25.860
I mean, it's not out of my head.

00:41:25.860 --> 00:41:32.210
But I had a mission.

00:41:35.074 --> 00:41:37.615
At the end of "Alone Together,"
all these people were saying,

00:41:37.615 --> 00:41:40.540
I'd rather text than talk.

00:41:40.540 --> 00:41:42.500
And I thought, I'm
a psychologist.

00:41:42.500 --> 00:41:47.720
If they really mean it, there
are profound implications

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:50.770
for how kids are growing up, how
loving partners are relating,

00:41:50.770 --> 00:41:59.870
how business is being done,
what families look like, what

00:41:59.870 --> 00:42:03.500
solitude is looking like.

00:42:03.500 --> 00:42:06.550
I want to do a kind of
ethnography of conversation

00:42:06.550 --> 00:42:08.370
in America.

00:42:08.370 --> 00:42:13.600
And if they mean it,
I want to tell them

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:17.070
that conversation is the
talking cure for the failing

00:42:17.070 --> 00:42:18.720
connections of our digital life.

00:42:21.640 --> 00:42:23.600
And they meant it.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:27.650
There was this flight from
conversation that I really

00:42:27.650 --> 00:42:30.960
hadn't-- "Alone Together"
really wasn't in a position

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:31.800
to document that.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:36.030
It was about 1,000 other things.

00:42:36.030 --> 00:42:42.590
So I was on a mission, which
was very different than "Alone

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:45.995
Together," where I'd done 15
years of NSF-funded research,

00:42:45.995 --> 00:42:48.469
and I reported out.

00:42:48.469 --> 00:42:50.510
Or the same thing for "The
Second Self" and "Life

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:51.680
on the Screen."

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:55.274
Whereas here, I kind
of wanted to know,

00:42:55.274 --> 00:42:57.440
what was the state of
conversation in America today?

00:42:57.440 --> 00:43:03.030
And if so, I felt very
strongly about conversation,

00:43:03.030 --> 00:43:07.220
based on my life as a
psychologist and my training.

00:43:07.220 --> 00:43:14.900
And I don't see why technology
can't be pro-conversation.

00:43:14.900 --> 00:43:17.950
In other words, I think this is
absolutely a false dichotomy.

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:22.085
I don't think technology has
to take a stand against-- you

00:43:22.085 --> 00:43:26.700
don't need to be anti-technology
to be pro-conversation.

00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:30.140
I'm pro-technology,
pro-conversation.

00:43:30.140 --> 00:43:35.700
So the idea that you're taking
a stand against technology

00:43:35.700 --> 00:43:41.170
to be pro-conversation I think
is just very bad for technology

00:43:41.170 --> 00:43:44.560
to be put in a position
where it's taking

00:43:44.560 --> 00:43:46.670
a stand against conversation.

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:49.600
That has to end, because
that is not sustainable.

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:52.740
So this is just the last thing
I would say before questions,

00:43:52.740 --> 00:43:55.030
that really I think the
future for a company

00:43:55.030 --> 00:43:59.890
like this is to get on the
conversation bandwagon.

00:43:59.890 --> 00:44:07.160
Because you want to find a way
to have conversation be part

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:12.160
of your message, conversation
be part of your product,

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:16.900
technology be easily
integrated into conversation.

00:44:16.900 --> 00:44:21.160
Just like you don't want
computer-assisted learning

00:44:21.160 --> 00:44:25.180
to be an anti-conversation
strategy.

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:27.120
You don't want
computer-assisted learning

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:30.410
to be something that closes
down conversation in schools.

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:33.640
And if you find
applications of computers

00:44:33.640 --> 00:44:37.310
in schools that are closing down
conversations in classrooms,

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:39.930
you want to change
those applications.

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:48.160
I mean, I think that both
the money and the-- it's

00:44:48.160 --> 00:44:49.790
not just the money.

00:44:49.790 --> 00:44:50.850
But let's say the money.

00:44:50.850 --> 00:44:53.510
I mean, the money-- I'll
take it on any level.

00:44:53.510 --> 00:44:55.180
I mean, it's the
money, the humanism,

00:44:55.180 --> 00:44:59.630
the forwardness, the future,
is for the corporate world

00:44:59.630 --> 00:45:04.420
to enhance conversation, enhance
learning, enhance excitement.

00:45:04.420 --> 00:45:06.539
You don't want
students who don't

00:45:06.539 --> 00:45:08.080
want to come talk
to their professors

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:10.050
because they think
that they'll get

00:45:10.050 --> 00:45:13.610
the right-- this
transactional model is not

00:45:13.610 --> 00:45:18.450
where you want to go.

00:45:18.450 --> 00:45:19.970
Yeah, so I wouldn't
mind everybody

00:45:19.970 --> 00:45:21.140
at Google reading my book.

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:23.950
I think that that would be good.

00:45:23.950 --> 00:45:24.950
LOGAN URY: That's great.

00:45:24.950 --> 00:45:26.330
OK, well let's open it up.

00:45:26.330 --> 00:45:27.510
Let's be pro-conversation--

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:28.330
SHERRY TURKLE: Pro-conversation.

00:45:28.330 --> 00:45:30.163
LOGAN URY: --and open
it up to the audience.

00:45:30.163 --> 00:45:33.022
OK, so just stand up, and
Scott will bring you the mic.

00:45:33.022 --> 00:45:33.881
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:45:33.881 --> 00:45:34.380
It's on.

00:45:34.380 --> 00:45:35.171
AUDIENCE: Is it on?

00:45:35.171 --> 00:45:35.850
Great.

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:38.440
I thought I might start,
if you don't mind.

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:40.790
