00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:45.890
Do you have any thoughts
about online dating

00:45:45.890 --> 00:45:48.370
and what happens
when relationships

00:45:48.370 --> 00:45:49.850
are conceived online?

00:45:49.850 --> 00:45:53.510
And so all of the initial
courtship occurs digitally,

00:45:53.510 --> 00:45:54.670
and then they finally meet.

00:45:54.670 --> 00:45:56.090
And I don't know
what happens there.

00:45:56.090 --> 00:45:58.423
SHERRY TURKLE: Well, I've had
some hysterical interviews

00:45:58.423 --> 00:46:00.680
with people who meet online,
and both partners don't

00:46:00.680 --> 00:46:05.970
want to end the online part.

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:14.040
So finally one will say,
well, how long can this go on?

00:46:14.040 --> 00:46:18.560
Because the online part is
so fulfilling because you're

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:21.070
very busy.

00:46:21.070 --> 00:46:25.160
You're very-- either it's
going to get fantastic,

00:46:25.160 --> 00:46:26.850
or it's going to end.

00:46:26.850 --> 00:46:28.890
Everybody feels that
way about dating.

00:46:28.890 --> 00:46:32.510
And online, you can be
the person you want to be.

00:46:32.510 --> 00:46:35.580
They're being the
person they want to be.

00:46:35.580 --> 00:46:38.810
And they're being the person who
they think you want them to be.

00:46:38.810 --> 00:46:42.500
You're both being the
person you think--

00:46:42.500 --> 00:46:44.350
we've all become very
good at picking up

00:46:44.350 --> 00:46:47.300
online signals of who we
should be for other people.

00:46:47.300 --> 00:46:49.530
I mean, that's another
skill set that's

00:46:49.530 --> 00:46:51.930
being developed that
who knew we had,

00:46:51.930 --> 00:46:53.505
of being able to
be-- I mean, that's

00:46:53.505 --> 00:46:56.810
a new kind of empathy
that's useful,

00:46:56.810 --> 00:46:59.570
but sort of gets
us into trouble.

00:46:59.570 --> 00:47:04.610
Online, you know how to pick
up this new kind of empathy

00:47:04.610 --> 00:47:06.920
that I don't even want to
call empathy because you're

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:13.080
playing to a fantasy thing.

00:47:13.080 --> 00:47:15.230
It's not the old
kind of empathy.

00:47:15.230 --> 00:47:17.460
It's not doing the work of
the old-fashioned empathy.

00:47:17.460 --> 00:47:20.960
So I interviewed so many
people who could not get

00:47:20.960 --> 00:47:22.570
that real person into the room.

00:47:25.240 --> 00:47:29.820
I would say that you want to get
the real person into the room.

00:47:29.820 --> 00:47:32.490
The idea that the longer
you keep it online,

00:47:32.490 --> 00:47:36.776
the better it's going
to be because-- I would

00:47:36.776 --> 00:47:39.220
say the longer it's
kept online, the greater

00:47:39.220 --> 00:47:41.180
the chance that the
person who shows up

00:47:41.180 --> 00:47:46.550
is going to be nothing like
the rare and totally perfect

00:47:46.550 --> 00:47:50.102
creature that you've been
talking with for 18 months.

00:47:50.102 --> 00:47:51.580
