00:48:43.074 --> 00:48:43.740
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:48:43.740 --> 00:48:45.432
And this is my question.

00:48:45.432 --> 00:48:46.890
The two things that
leap to my mind

00:48:46.890 --> 00:48:50.130
are largely historical when
I think about my resistance

00:48:50.130 --> 00:48:51.210
to these.

00:48:51.210 --> 00:48:52.500
We've had some of this before.

00:48:52.500 --> 00:48:55.800
This doesn't at least
seem to me to be that new.

00:48:55.800 --> 00:48:57.770
You have to kind of
go back in time a bit.

00:48:57.770 --> 00:48:59.445
So a lot of what
you've talked about--

00:48:59.445 --> 00:49:00.450
SHERRY TURKLE: Like the book?

00:49:00.450 --> 00:49:01.650
AUDIENCE: The book
and letters were

00:49:01.650 --> 00:49:02.900
the two things that struck me.

00:49:02.900 --> 00:49:04.710
So I'm really curious
if you had a chance

00:49:04.710 --> 00:49:07.190
to look at kind of
historically how

00:49:07.190 --> 00:49:09.560
the rise of the cheap
paperback, for example,

00:49:09.560 --> 00:49:14.240
and the experience of letters
challenged conversation

00:49:14.240 --> 00:49:15.410
in their historical periods.

00:49:15.410 --> 00:49:16.201
SHERRY TURKLE: Yes.

00:49:16.201 --> 00:49:19.520
And I'm only sorry that
I didn't stop the book

00:49:19.520 --> 00:49:23.160
and say, and now let me talk
about the book and letters,

00:49:23.160 --> 00:49:26.400
because I should have.

00:49:26.400 --> 00:49:29.110
But since I didn't, let me
just talk about it here.

00:49:29.110 --> 00:49:32.010
So how many times have you
been talking to somebody--

00:49:32.010 --> 00:49:34.420
if I went, you know what?

00:49:34.420 --> 00:49:39.050
We're in this conversation,
but what I really want to do

00:49:39.050 --> 00:49:43.913
is read, like, three
paragraphs of "Madame Bovary."

00:49:43.913 --> 00:49:45.246
LOGAN URY: Never happened to me.

00:49:45.246 --> 00:49:48.620
SHERRY TURKLE: So hold on.

00:49:48.620 --> 00:49:50.886
I'll just get right back to you.

00:49:50.886 --> 00:49:52.960
And you go to "Madame Bovary."

00:49:52.960 --> 00:49:55.500
You read your paragraphs,
maybe just one paragraph.

00:49:55.500 --> 00:49:57.960
AUDIENCE: Oh, I will
say kids do that.

00:49:57.960 --> 00:49:59.055
Kids will do that.

00:49:59.055 --> 00:49:59.930
SHERRY TURKLE: Right.

00:49:59.930 --> 00:50:03.960
But you read a little "Madame
Bovary," and then you just say,

00:50:03.960 --> 00:50:05.760
I'm back.

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:11.400
So it's what Linda Stone called
continual partial attention,

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:18.723
is that it's the
lack of segregation.

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:27.240
Because I think the book thing
is very important, more so

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:30.650
than the television example,
because in this book,

00:50:30.650 --> 00:50:33.410
I use television as
a good example of how

00:50:33.410 --> 00:50:37.100
we can turn things around.

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:39.960
Television is an example
of people jumping around

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:42.390
and making all kinds of
fuss about a technology that

00:50:42.390 --> 00:50:45.636
could be used socially if you
wanted it to be used socially.

00:50:45.636 --> 00:50:47.052
And why everybody
assumed that you

00:50:47.052 --> 00:50:49.190
were going to be using
this not socially

00:50:49.190 --> 00:50:51.850
is just like part
of the zeitgeist,

00:50:51.850 --> 00:50:54.110
that people saw it as
destroying the family.

00:50:54.110 --> 00:50:57.260
But in my family, watching
television was a contact sport.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:51:01.051
So we sat around, watching
television and arguing

00:51:01.051 --> 00:51:02.800
about what was happening
on the television

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:04.966
and fighting about what the
people on the television

00:51:04.966 --> 00:51:05.570
were doing.

00:51:05.570 --> 00:51:08.410
Well, it brought the
family completely together.

00:51:08.410 --> 00:51:11.860
I watch television
with my daughter.

00:51:11.860 --> 00:51:13.885
I mean, we watch
television together.

00:51:16.710 --> 00:51:18.364
Obviously she's
graduated college now,

00:51:18.364 --> 00:51:20.780
so she actually has less time
to watch television with me.

00:51:20.780 --> 00:51:22.446
But we watch "Game
of Thrones" together,

00:51:22.446 --> 00:51:26.560
and it's like our closest--
when they killed off

00:51:26.560 --> 00:51:31.910
that whole family, I was
like, no fuckin' way.

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:32.920
I jumped up.

00:51:36.541 --> 00:51:39.459
It's a very social--
watching "Game of Thrones,"

00:51:39.459 --> 00:51:40.250
that's another tip.

00:51:40.250 --> 00:51:41.874
I don't know if it's
a tip for romance,

00:51:41.874 --> 00:51:44.360
but it's definitely a tip.

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:47.320
It's definitely a
tip for families who

00:51:47.320 --> 00:51:49.560
feel they want to get closer.

00:51:49.560 --> 00:51:53.860
I'm very big on television,
games, card games.

00:51:53.860 --> 00:51:56.512
The point is, it's a technology,
but it's a technology

00:51:56.512 --> 00:51:57.720
of talking and socialization.

00:51:57.720 --> 00:51:59.180
The point is that.

00:51:59.180 --> 00:52:02.740
So television is a great example
of how it's not the technology,

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:04.870
it's the social context.

00:52:04.870 --> 00:52:09.304
So the trouble with
this kind of-- this

00:52:09.304 --> 00:52:10.720
is because you're
telling somebody

00:52:10.720 --> 00:52:14.897
who literally is-- you're in
the middle of a conversation.

00:52:14.897 --> 00:52:15.855
You're a tape recorder.

00:52:15.855 --> 00:52:17.110
I'm putting you on pause.

00:52:17.110 --> 00:52:19.080
I'm going to the
people in my phone.

00:52:19.080 --> 00:52:22.460
Or I have a lot of
data on how people

00:52:22.460 --> 00:52:24.720
use this thing called
this rule of three,

00:52:24.720 --> 00:52:27.330
where they're sitting at dinner.

00:52:27.330 --> 00:52:29.880
You're six, and three people
have to have their heads

00:52:29.880 --> 00:52:32.820
up before you go
down to your phone.

00:52:32.820 --> 00:52:36.230
And it's basically just
the same as in the--

00:52:36.230 --> 00:52:40.240
which is how college students
behave in dining halls.

00:52:40.240 --> 00:52:42.800
And the conversation
stays light,

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:45.210
and people don't feel
connected to each other.

00:52:45.210 --> 00:52:51.530
So that's the social norms
around using the phone.

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:58.970
People don't, at dinner, say,
we're at dinner together,

00:52:58.970 --> 00:53:05.240
and I'm going to just read
a few paragraphs of my book.

00:53:05.240 --> 00:53:07.350
Now, that's because
we have social norms.

00:53:07.350 --> 00:53:09.290
It's not because they couldn't.

00:53:09.290 --> 00:53:12.670
It's because we've just
evolved social norms that say,

00:53:12.670 --> 00:53:13.930
really, no.

00:53:13.930 --> 00:53:14.560
Not.

00:53:14.560 --> 00:53:15.510
Don't do that.

00:53:15.510 --> 00:53:17.820
And we can do that
for our phones.

00:53:17.820 --> 00:53:19.120
So that's kind of my message.

00:53:19.120 --> 00:53:20.930
It's not the phone.

00:53:20.930 --> 00:53:24.380
It's that, how did it
come to pass in the past--

00:53:24.380 --> 00:53:26.320
so as I was watching
this, this thing

00:53:26.320 --> 00:53:28.671
unfolded, this rule of three.

00:53:28.671 --> 00:53:30.420
How did it come to
pass that it was really

00:53:30.420 --> 00:53:33.870
fine to go to dinner with four
people, and have two of them

00:53:33.870 --> 00:53:35.370
on their phone?

00:53:35.370 --> 00:53:38.255
And that's like what going
out with my faculty colleagues

00:53:38.255 --> 00:53:40.380
is like.

00:53:40.380 --> 00:53:42.700
That is not unusual.

00:53:42.700 --> 00:53:46.390
And you say, why
is the phone here?

00:53:46.390 --> 00:53:49.260
And they'll say, an emergency.

00:53:49.260 --> 00:53:52.372
And then you ask
them-- I mean, I'm

00:53:52.372 --> 00:53:54.080
allowed to ask them
because it's like I'm

00:53:54.080 --> 00:53:57.320
pretending it's research.

00:53:57.320 --> 00:53:59.150
What emergency?

00:53:59.150 --> 00:54:02.450
And the bar is very low.

00:54:02.450 --> 00:54:05.050
The bar is very low.

00:54:05.050 --> 00:54:06.300
The bar is very low.

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:08.225
And that's what this
book is arguing,

00:54:08.225 --> 00:54:11.130
that these are social rules.

00:54:11.130 --> 00:54:13.430
We've just invented them.

00:54:13.430 --> 00:54:15.710
They're extremely new.

00:54:15.710 --> 00:54:19.010
And we didn't invent
them for the book.

00:54:19.010 --> 00:54:22.150
And let's un-invent
them for the phone.

00:54:22.150 --> 00:54:25.090
And that this is work
we know how to do.

00:54:25.090 --> 00:54:27.230
I love my favorite
example-- I mean,

00:54:27.230 --> 00:54:29.150
